# Passing Data Down

**Props** are arguments passed into React components. They are like function parameters – they let you customise a component when you use it.

* Props are **read‑only** – a component cannot modify its own props.
* Props can be any JavaScript value: strings, numbers, objects, arrays, functions, even other components.

## Example

```jsx
// Child component
function Greeting(props) {
  return <Text>Hello, {props.name}!</Text>;
}

// Parent component
function App() {
  return <Greeting name="Alice" />;
}
```

## Cleaner Code with Destructuring

Instead of writing `props.name`, you can destructure the props object directly in the function parameter.

```jsx
function Greeting({ name, age }) {
  return (
    <Text>
      {name} is {age} years old.
    </Text>
  );
}

// Usage
<Greeting name="Bob" age={30} />
```

This is a common pattern in React and makes the component's expected props clear.

slides.codeSnippet:
function UserCard({ name, email, isVerified }) {
  return (
    <View style={{ padding: 10, borderWidth: 1 }}>
      <Text style={{ fontWeight: 'bold' }}>{name}</Text>
      <Text>{email}</Text>
      {isVerified && <Text>✅ Verified</Text>}
    </View>
  );
}

// Usage
<UserCard
  name="Alice Wonder"
  email="alice@example.com"
  isVerified={true}
/>

